Within the United Nations, real power is located in the Security Council, where five of the 15 countries have veto power. (Image: Andrzej Krauze) That veto power, which the US, UK, and France have used in recent years, gives them the ability to block any resolution against their own interests. The Security Council's five permanent members are China, France, Russia, the UK, and the US. The ten elected members can block any resolution but cannot veto one. Currently, five of those ten are African states.
